ar role in]]:\n*'''Severe [[asthma]]'''\n*'''[[Beh\u00e7et's disease|Beh\u00e7et's]]'''\n*'''[[Hashimoto's encephalopathy]]'''\n*'''[[Juvenile idiopathic arthritis|Juvenile arthritis]]''' \n | Autoimmunity, unclear role. \n | See respective conditions \n | See respective conditions \n | {{OMIM7|172430|ENO1}}\n |- valign=\"top\"\n | Glycolysis step 9 <br/>[[Enolase]]&nbsp;3<br/>(Beta-enolase,<br/>\u03b2-enolase) \n | [[ENO3]]: <br/>Muscle <hr/>  '''[[Glycogen storage disease type XIII|GSD type XIII]]''' <br/>(GSD 13, \u03b2-enolase deficiency, beta-enolase deficiency, enolase 3 deficiency, muscle enolase deficiency) \n | Myopathy. Exercise-induced myalgias, generalized muscle weakness and fatigability. \n | <!--Diagnose--> '''Exercise test''': No rise of lactate. <br/> '''Biopsy''': Focal sarcoplasmic accumulation of glycogen-beta particles. Immunohistochemistry and immunoblotting show reduced beta-enolase protein.\n | <!--Treatment--> No treatment information in references given.\n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/ENO3 ENO3] <br/>{{OMIM7|131370|ENO3}} <hr/> {{OMIM7|612932|GSD XIII}} <br/> {{GARD1|2125|GSD XIII}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|99849|GSD XIII}}\n |- valign=\"top\"\n | {{nowrap|Glycolysis step 10}}<br/>[[Pyruvate kinase]] \n | [[PKLR]]: <br/>RBCs, liver <hr/> '''[[Pyruvate kinase deficiency]]''' <br/>(PK deficiency, PKD) \n | Hemolytic anemia. \n | <!--Diagnose-->\n | <!--Treatment-->\n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/PKLR PKLR] <br/>{{OMIM7|609712|PKLR}} <hr/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/pyruvate-kinase-deficiency PKD] <br/> {{OMIM7|266200|PKD}} <br/> {{GARD1|7514|PKD}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|766|PKD}}\n|}\n\n===== Related to glycolysis =====\nThe [[pyruvate]] created by glycolysis (in the [[cytosol]]) is transported (together with a proton) to the [[mitochondrion]] for further energy extraction.\n\nUnder [[Anaerobic respiration|anaerobic conditions]] (without the use of oxygen) most if not all of the [[Lactate dehydrogenase|pyruvate is converted]] to [[lactic acid|lactate]] (furthermore producing NADH at the same time).\n\nUnder [[cellular respiration|aerobic conditions]] (with the use of oxygen) only part of the pyruvate is converted to lactate; the pyruvate not converted feeds the [[citric acid cycle|citric acid cycle (CAC)]]; both via [[pyruvate dehydrogenase]] ([[Pyruvate dehydrogenase complex|PDC]], with [[Acetyl-CoA]] as intermediate) and via [[pyruvate decarboxylation]] - this will create further ATP and NADH for the cell's use.\n\n(See also [[bioenergetic systems]].)\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n |- valign=\"top\" \n ! Related enzymatic function <br/>\u2013<br/> Enzyme <br/> (Relation)\n ! Gene: <br/> Organ(s) <hr/> Disease<br/>(Synonyms) \n ! {{nowrap|Reported symptoms.}} <br/> Forms (if applicable) <br> {{nobold|{{small|Note: Not all patients have all symptoms; severity and presentation can vary.}}}}\n ! Diagnostic tests \n ! Management and treatment \n ! References <br/> and links \n |- valign=\"top\"\n | Pyruvate <!-- transport ??? / --> dehydrogenation / decarboxylation.  {{Center|\u2013}} [[Pyruvate dehydrogenase complex]] \n | PDHA1, PDHX, PDHB, DLAT, PDP1 <br/>Systemic/various<hr/> '''[[Pyruvate dehydrogenase deficiency]]''' <br/> (PDHA deficiency, PDHAD, ataxia with lactic acidosis, intermittent ataxia with pyruvate dehydrogenase deficiency, pyruvate dehydrogenase complex deficiency, pyruvate decarboxylase deficiency) \n | 2 major presentations: metabolic and neurologic. Broad clinical spectrum: From fatal lactic acidosis in the newborn to chronic neurologic dysfunction with structural abnormalities in the central nervous system without systemic acidosis. Most common cause of primary lactic acidosis in children.\n | <!-- Diagnose -->\n | <!-- Treatment -->\n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/PDHA1 PDHA1] <br/>{{OMIM7|300502|PDHA1}} <hr/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/pyruvate-dehydrogenase-deficiency PDHAD] <br/> {{OMIM7|312170|PDHAD}} <br/> {{GARD1|4620|PDHAD}} <br/> {{GARD1|7513|PDHAD}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|765|PDHAD}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|79243|PDHAD}}\n |- valign=\"top\"\n | Inter-conversion of [[Pyruvic acid|pyruvate]] and [[Lactic acid|lactate]]. {{Center|\u2013}} [[Lactate dehydrogenase A|Lactate dehydrogenase&nbsp;A]] \n | [[LDHA]]: <br/> Muscle <hr/>  '''[[Glycogen storage disease type XI|GSD type XI]]''' <br/> (GSD 11, lactate dehydrogenase deficiency, LDH deficiency) \n | Myopathy. Exercise intolerance.\n\nNote: Deficiency of dehydrogenase-B (LDHB) has been observed as asymptomatic.\n | <!-- Diagnose --> '''Exercise test''': Increased pyruvate, but no rise of lactate.\n | <!-- Treatment --> No treatment information in references given.\n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/LDHA LDHA] <br/>{{OMIM7|150000|LDHA}} <hr/> {{nowrap|NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/lactate-dehydrogenase-deficiency GSD 11]}} <br/> {{OMIM7|612933|GSD 11}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|2364|GSD 11}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|284426|GSD 11}}\n|}\n\nMitochondrial pyruvate carrier deficiency (MPYCD) is a metabolic disorder, in which the transport of pyruvate from the cystol to the mitochondria is affected (gene BRP44L/MPC1<ref>{{OMIM7|614738|BRP44L}}</ref>); the deficiency is characterized by delayed psychomotor development and lactic acidosis with a normal lactate/pyruvate ratio resulting from impaired mitochondrial pyruvate oxidation.<ref>{{OMIM7|614741|MPYCD}}</ref>\n\n==== Gluconeogenesis ====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n |- valign=\"top\" \n ! [[Gluconeogenesis]] step {{Center|\u2013}} Enzyme\n ! Gene: <br/> Organ(s) <hr/> Disease<br/>(Synonyms) \n ! {{nowrap|Reported symptoms.}} <br/> Forms (if applicable) <br> {{nobold|{{small|Note: Not all patients have all symptoms; severity and presentation can vary.}}}}\n ! Diagnostic tests \n ! Treatment \n ! References <br/> and links \n |- valign=\"top\"\n | [[Gluconeogenesis]] step 8 {{Center|\u2013}} [[Fructose 1,6-bisphosphatase]] \n | [[FBP1]]: <br/> Liver <hr/>  '''[[Fructose bisphosphatase deficiency]]''' <br/>(FBP1, Baker-Winegrad disease) \n | Fasting hypoglycemia with lactic acidosis. Episodes of hyperventilation, apnea, and ketosis. Symptoms exacerbated by fructose, sucrose, and glycerol consumption. \n | <!-- Diagnose -->\n | <!-- Treatment -->\n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/FBP1 FBP1] <br/>{{OMIM7|611570|FBP1}} <hr/> {{OMIM7|229700|FBP1D}} <br/> {{GARD1|2400|FBP1D}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|348|FBP1D}}\n |- valign=\"top\"\n | Gluconeogenesis step 10 (final step): <br/> Conversion of G-1-P to glucose {{Center|\u2013}} [[Glucose 6-phosphatase]] \n | [[G6PC]]: <br/> Liver <br/> [[SLC37A4]]&nbsp;(G6PT1): <br/> Liver <hr/>  '''[[Glycogen storage disease type I|GSD type I]]''' <br/> (GSD 1, von Gierke's disease, hepatorenal glycogenosis, glucose-6-phosphate deficiency, glucose-6-phosphate transport defect) \n | Hypoglycemia and hepatomegaly. Growth retardation, delayed puberty, lactic acidemia, hyperlipidemia, hyperuricemia. In adults hepatic adenomas likely.  \n | <!-- Diagnose --> '''Exercise test''': Normal lactate and ammonia rise.<ref name=\"ischaemic\"/>\n | <!-- Treatment -->\n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/G6PC G6PC] <br/>{{OMIM7|613742|G6PC}} <br/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/SLC37A4 SLC37A4] <br/>{{OMIM7|602671|SLC37A4}} <hr/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/glycogen-storage-disease-type-i GSD 1] <br/> {{ORPHA1|364|GSD 1}} <br/> {{OMIM7|232200|GSD 1a}} <br/> {{GARD1|7864|GSD 1a}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|79258|GSD 1a}} <br/> {{OMIM7|232220|GSD 1b}} <br/> {{GARD1|2515|GSD 1b}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|79259|GSD 1b}} <br/> {{OMIM7|232240|GSD 1c/1d}} \n |- valign=\"top\"\n | Gluconeogenesis step 10 (final step): <br/> Conversion of G-1-P to glucose {{Center|\u2013}} [[Glucose 6-phosphatase]] \n | [[G6PC3]]: <br/> WBCs, heart, others <hr/> '''Severe congenital [[neutropenia]] type 4''' <br/> (SCN4, congenital agranulocytosis, congenital neutropenia, Kostmann's disease, severe congenital neutropenia-pulmonary hypertension-superficial venous angiectasis) <br/> '''Dursun syndrome''' <br/> (DURSS, pulmonary arterial hypertension-leukopenia-atrial septal defect syndrome)\n | '''SCN4''': A disorder of hematopoiesis. Maturation arrest of granulopoiesis at the level of promyelocytes. Neutropenia. Osteopenia, may lead to osteoporosis. Prone to recurrent infections. In some heart and genital abnormalities, cancerous conditions of the blood, seizures, developmental delay. <br/> '''Dursun syndrome''': Pulmonary arterial hypertension, cardiac abnormalities (including secundum-type atrial septal defect), intermittent neutropenia, lymphopenia, monocytosis and anemia. \n | <!-- Diagnose -->\n | <!-- Treatment -->\n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/G6PC3 G6PC3] <br/>{{OMIM7|611045|G6PC3}} <hr/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/severe-congenital-neutropenia SCN4] <br/> {{OMIM7|612541|SCN4}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|331176|SCN4}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|178503|DURSS}}\n|}\n\n=== Glycogen metabolism ===\n\n==== Glycogenesis ====\n[[File:Glycogenesis.png|thumb]]\n[[Glycogenesis]] is the [[metabolic pathway]] in which [[glycogen]] is created. Glycogen, which consists of branched [[polysaccharide|long chains]] made out of the [[monosaccharide|simple sugar]] [[glucose]], is an energy storage form for [[carbohydrate]]s in many human cells; this is most important in [[liver]], [[muscle]] and [[Astrocytes|certain brain cells]].\n\nThe monosaccharide [[glucose-6-phosphate]] (G-6-P) is typically the [[Substrate (chemistry)|input substance]] for glycogenesis. G-6-P is most commonly created from glucose by the action of the [[enzyme]]s [[glucokinase]] (see glycolysis step 1) or [[hexokinase]].\n\nThrough the action of several enzymes glycogen is build up:<!--Taken from [[Glycogenesis]] -->\n* G-6-P is converted into [[glucose-1-phosphate]] (G-1-P) by the action of [[phosphoglucomutase]] (PGM), passing through the obligatory intermediate [[glucose-1,6-bisphosphate]].\n* G-1-P is converted into [[UDP-glucose]] by the action of the enzyme [[UTP\u2014glucose-1-phosphate uridylyltransferase|UDP-glucose pyrophosphorylase]] (UGP).\n* The enzyme [[glycogenin]] (GYG) is needed to create initial short glycogen chains, which are lengthened and branched by the other enzymes of glycogenesis.\n* Once eight glucose have been added to the glycogen chain, then [[glycogen synthase]] (GYS) can bind to the growing glycogen chain and add UDP-glucose to lengthen the glucogen chain.\n* Branches are made by [[glycogen branching enzyme]] (GBE), which transfers the end of the chain onto an earlier part, forming branches; these grow further grow by addition of more units.\n\nOn an alternative metabolic pathway the simple sugar [[galactose]] (Gal, which is typically derived from [[lactose]]) is converted by the enzyme [[galactokinase]] (GALK) to [[galactose-1-phosphate]] (Gal-1-P), which in turn is converted by the enzyme [[galactose-1-phosphate uridylyltransferase]] (GALT) to [[glucose-1-phosphate]] (G-1-P), which can also serve as input for glycogenesis \u2013 this bypasses the first step of glycogenesis (the enzyme [[phosphoglucomutase]] PGM).\n\nErrors in glycogenesis can have different consequences on a cellular level:\n* Too little glycogen is produced, e.g. in GSD 0\n* The glycogen is badly formed and inaccessible, typically accumulating in the affected cells (e.g. polyglucosan bodies).\nDepending on the affected cells and the extent of the deficiency, a wide range of symptoms and severities are the result.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n |- valign=\"top\" \n ! [[Glycogenesis]]&nbsp;step <br/>\u2013<br/> Enzyme \n ! Gene: <br/>Organ(s) <hr/> Disease<br/>(Synonyms) \n ! {{nowrap|Reported symptoms.}} <br/> Forms (if applicable) <br> {{nobold|{{small|Note: Not all patients have all symptoms; severity and presentation can vary.}}}}\n ! Diagnostic tests \n ! Treatment \n ! References <br/> and links \n |- valign=\"top\"\n | [[Glycogenesis]] step: <br/> Inter-conversion of G-1-P and G-6-P {{Center|\u2013}} [[Phosphoglucomutase]]&nbsp;1 <br/> (Also last step of glycogenolysis)\n | [[PGM1]]: <br/> Liver, muscle, other <hr/> {{nowrap|'''[[Congenital disorder of glycosylation|CDG syndrome]] type It'''}} <br/> (CDG1T, PGM1-CDG, phosphoglucomutase 1 deficiency, PGM1 deficiency) <br/> formerly: '''GSD type XIV''' <br/> (GSD 14) \n | Wide range of manifestations and severity. Commonly cleft lip and bifid uvula, hepatopathy, intermittent hypoglycemia, short stature, and exercise intolerance. \n | <!--Diagnose--> \n | <!--Treatment--> \n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/PGM1 PGM1] <br/>{{OMIM7|171900|PGM1}} <hr/> {{OMIM7|614921|CDG 1T}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|319646|CDG 1T}}\n |- valign=\"top\"\n | [[Glycogenesis]] step: <br/> [[UDP-glucose]] synthesis {{Center|\u2013}} [[UTP\u2014glucose-1-phosphate uridylyltransferase|UDP-glucose pyrophosphorylase]] \n | UGP2 <br/> <!-- Organ <hr/> '''Disease''' <br\\> (Synonym) --> No known inborn disease, included for completeness.\n | -\n | -\n | -\n | {{OMIM7|191760|UGP2}}\n |- valign=\"top\"\n | [[Glycogenesis]] step: <br/> Glycogen primer synthesis {{Center|\u2013}} [[Glycogenin]] \n | [[GYG1]]: <br/> Muscle <hr/>  '''[[Glycogen storage disease type XV|GSD type XV]]''' <br/> (GSD 15, glycogenin deficiency) <br/> '''[[Polyglucosan body myopathy]] type 2''' <br/>(PGBM2) \n | '''GSD 15''': Myopathy, cardiomyopathy. Rare. Muscle weakness. <br/> '''PGBM2''': Myopathy. Proximal muscle weakness of the lower limbs, gait disturbances. Upper limbs and/or distal muscle weakness in some. Onset-age highly variable, slowly progressive.\n | <!--Diagnose--> '''Exercise test''': ? <br/> '''Skeletal muscle biopsy''': deficit of glycogen, predominance of slow-twitch, oxidative muscle fibers and mitochondrial proliferation. <br/> '''Endomyocardial biopsy''': hypertrophic cardiomyocytes, enlarged nuclei and large centrally located vacuoles containing periodic acid Schiff (PAS)-positive material (but ultrastructurally different from glycogen). Glycogen depletion in the remainder of the cytoplasm. \n | <!--Treatment--> No treatment information in references given.\n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/GYG1 GYG1] <br/>{{OMIM7|603942|GYG1}} <hr/> {{OMIM7|613507|GSD 15}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|263297|GSD 15}}\n\n{{OMIM7|616199|PGBM2}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|456369|PGBM2}} \n |- valign=\"top\"\n | [[Glycogenesis]] step: <br/> Glucogen chain lengthening {{Center|\u2013}} [[Glycogen synthase]] \n | GYS1: <br/> Muscle <hr/>  '''[[Glycogen storage disease type 0|GSD type 0]]b''' <br/>(GSD 0b, glycogen synthetase deficiency) \n | Myopathy, cardiomyopathy, exercise intolerance.\n | <!--Diagnose--> '''Exercise test''': ?\n | <!--Treatment--> \n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/GYS2 GYS2] <br/>{{OMIM7|138571|GYS2}} <hr/> {{OMIM7|611556|GSD 0B}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|137625|GSD 0B}}\n |- valign=\"top\"\n | [[Glycogenesis]] step: <br/> Glucogen chain lengthening {{Center|\u2013}} [[Glycogen synthase]] \n | [[GYS2]]: <br/> Liver <hr/>  '''[[Glycogen storage disease type 0|GSD type 0]]a''' <br/>(GSD 0a, glycogen synthetase deficiency) \n | Infancy or in early childhood onset. Morning fatigue and fasting hypoglycemia, hyperketonemia. Without hepatomegaly, hyperalaninemia or hyperlactacidemia. After meals, major hyperglycemia associated with lactate and alanine increase and hyperlipidemia.\n | <!--Diagnose--> \n | <!--Treatment--> \n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/GYS2 GYS2] <br/>{{OMIM7|138571|GYS2}} <hr/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/glycogen-storage-disease-type-0 GSD 0] <br/> {{OMIM7|240600|GSD 0A}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|2089|GSD 0A}}\n |- valign=\"top\"\n | [[Glycogenesis]] step: <br/> Glucogen chain branching {{Center|\u2013}} [[Glycogen branching enzyme]] \n | [[GBE1]]: <br/> Liver, muscle <hr/>  '''[[Glycogen storage disease type IV|GSD type IV]]''' <br/>(GSD 4, Andersen's disease, amylopectinosis, brancher deficiency, glycogen branching enzyme deficiency, familial cirrhosis with deposition of abnormal glycogen) \n | Different forms have been described: \n* [http://www.orpha.net/consor/cgi-bin/OC_Exp.php?lng=EN&Expert=308684 Childhood combined hepatic and myopathic form]\n* [http://www.orpha.net/consor/cgi-bin/OC_Exp.php?lng=EN&Expert=308712 Adult neuromuscular form]\n* [http://www.orpha.net/consor/cgi-bin/OC_Exp.php?lng=EN&Expert=308698 Childhood neuromuscular form]\n* [http://www.orpha.net/consor/cgi-bin/OC_Exp.php?lng=EN&Expert=308670 Congenital neuromuscular form]\n* [http://www.orpha.net/consor/cgi-bin/OC_Exp.php?lng=EN&Expert=308621 Progressive hepatic form]\n* [http://www.orpha.net/consor/cgi-bin/OC_Exp.php?lng=EN&Expert=308655 Fatal perinatal neuromuscular form]\n* [http://www.orpha.net/consor/cgi-bin/OC_Exp.php?lng=EN&Expert=308638 Non progressive hepatic form]\n | <!--Diagnose--> Activity of branching enzyme in erythrocytes.\n | <!--Treatment--> High-protein diet. Liver transplant for progressive liver disease. Cardiomyopathy may require certain medications.\n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/GBE1 GBE1] <br/>{{OMIM7|607839|GBE1}} <hr/> {{nowrap|NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/glycogen-storage-disease-type-iv GSD 4]}} <br/> {{OMIM7|232500|GSD 4}} <br/> {{GARD1|2520|GSD 4}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|367|GSD 4}}\n |- valign=\"top\"\n | [[Glycogenesis]] step: <br/> Glucogen chain branching {{Center|\u2013}} [[Glycogen branching enzyme]] \n | [[GBE1]]: <br/> Nerve cells <hr/>  '''[[Adult polyglucosan body disease]]''' <br/>(APBD) \n | Neuropathy, affecting the central and peripheral nervous systems. Cognitive impairment, pyramidal tetraparesis, peripheral neuropathy, and neurogenic bladder. Peripheral neuropathy and progressive muscle weakness and stiffness (spasticity). Cerebellar dysfunction and extrapyramidal signs in some. Late-onset, slowly progressive.\n | <!--Diagnose--> \n | <!--Treatment--> \n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/GBE1 GBE1] <br/>{{OMIM7|607839|GBE1}} <hr/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/adult-polyglucosan-body-disease APBD] <br/> {{OMIM7|263570|APBD}} <br/> {{GARD1|108|APBD}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|206583|APBD}}\n|}\n\n==== Glycogenolysis ====\n[[Image:Glycogen.svg|thumb]]\nTo access the energy stored as [[glycogen]], cells use the [[metabolic pathway]] [[glycogenolysis]] (glycogen breakdown); this produces the [[monosaccharide|simple sugar]] [[glucose-6-phosphate]] (G-6-P), from which cells can [[cellular respiration|extract energy]] or build other substances (e.g. [[ribose]]s).\n\nG-6-P (which is also produced from glucose) acts as a [[Substrate (chemistry)|input substance]] for:\n* [[Glycolysis]] (see above)\n* The [[Pentose phosphate pathway]] (PPP)\n(See also [[bioenergetic systems]].)\n\nAn alternative to glycolysis is the [[Pentose phosphate pathway]] (PPP): Depending on cellular conditions the PPP can produce [[nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate|NADPH]] (another energy transport form [[intracellular|in the cell]]) or synthesize [[ribose]]s (important for substances based on ribose like e.g. [[RNA]]) - the PPP is for example important in [[red blood cell]]s.\n\n<!--Text taken from [[Phosphoglucomutase]] -->If glycogenolysis is taking place in the liver, G-6-P can be [[Gluconeogenesis|converted to glucose]] by the enzyme [[glucose 6-phosphatase]] (G6Pase); the glucose produced in the liver is then released to the bloodstream for use in other organs. Muscle cells in contrast do not have the enzyme glucose 6-phosphatase, so they cannot share their glycogen stores with the rest of the body.\n\nIn addition to glycogen breakdown with the glycogen debranching enzyme and the glycogen phosphorylase enzyme, cells also use the enzyme [[acid alpha-glucosidase]] in [[lysosome]]s to degrade glycogen.\n\nAn deficiency of an involved enzyme results in:\n* Accumulation of glycogen in the cells\n* Lack of cellular energy negatively affects the involved organs\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n |- valign=\"top\" \n ! [[Glycogenolysis]]&nbsp;step <br/>\u2013<br/> Enzyme \n ! Gene: <br/>Organ(s) <hr/> Disease<br/>(Synonyms) \n ! {{nowrap|Reported symptoms.}} <br/> Forms (if applicable) <br> {{nobold|{{small|Note: Not all patients have all symptoms; severity and presentation can vary.}}}}\n ! Diagnostic tests \n ! Treatment \n ! References <br/> and links \n |- valign=\"top\"\n | [[Glycogenolysis]]&nbsp;step: <br/> Release of G-1-P {{Center|\u2013}} [[Glycogen phosphorylase]] \n | [[PYGL]]: <br/> Liver <hr/> '''[[Glycogen storage disease type VI|GSD type VI]]''' <br/>(GSD 6, Hers disease, hepatic glycogen phosphorylase deficiency, liver phosphorylase deficiency syndrome) \n | Hepatomegaly, failure to thrive, growth retardation. No other developmental delay, no muscle involvement. Hypoglycemia, lactic acidosis, hyperlipidemia and ketosis during prolonged fasting periods. Infancy or childhood onset, symptoms tend to improve with age.\n | <!--Diagnose--> \n | <!--Treatment--> \n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/PYGL PYGL] <br/>{{OMIM7|613741|PYGL}} <hr/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/glycogen-storage-disease-type-vi GSD 6] <br/> {{OMIM7|232700|GSD 6}} <br/> {{GARD1|6529|GSD 6}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|369|GSD 6}}\n |- valign=\"top\"\n | [[Glycogenolysis]]&nbsp;step: <br/> Release of G-1-P {{Center|\u2013}} [[Glycogen phosphorylase]] \n | [[PYGM]]: <br/> Muscle <hr/> '''[[Glycogen storage disease type V|GSD type V]]''' <br/>(GSD 5, McArdle's disease, muscle phosphorylase deficiency, myophosphorylase deficiency, PYGM deficiency) \n | Myopathy: Exercise intolerance, symptoms tend to improve with rest. \"Second wind\" phenomenon in most. Rhabdomyolysis and myoglobinuria possible. Progressive muscle weakness worsens in two-thirds of affected individuals, however in some the muscle weakness is stable. <br/> '''Onset forms: infant, child, adult.''' Infant-form most severe (e.g. progressive respiratory failure), adult-onset can be very mild (e.g. mainly poor stamina).\n | <!--Diagnose--> '''Exercise test''': Severely impaired rise of lactate. Normal or enhanced ammonia.<ref name=\"ischaemic\">{{cite journal|last1=Livingstone|first1=Callum|last2=Chinnery|first2=Patrick F.|last3=Turnbull|first3=Douglass M.|year=2001|title=The ischaemic lactate-ammonia test|journal= Ann Clin Biochem|doi=10.1258/0004563011900786 |pmid=11471870|volume=38|issue=4|pages=304\u2013310}}</ref><ref name=\"ischaemic2\">{{cite journal|first1=P\u00e4ivi   |last1=Piiril\u00e4|first2=Mari|last2=Auranen|year=2016|title=Unique Exercise Lactate Profile in Muscle Phosphofructokinase Deficiency (Tarui Disease); Difference Compared with McArdle Disease.|journal=Front Neurol|doi=10.3389/fneur.2016.00082 |pmid=27303362|volume=7|pmc=4885106|page=82}}</ref><ref name=\"Gsd5LactatePNAS\">{{cite journal|first1=Nigel F.|last1=Delaney|first2=Vamsi K.|last2=Mootha|year=2017|title=Metabolic profiles of exercise in patients with McArdle disease or mitochondrial myopathy|journal=PNAS|doi=10.1073/pnas.1703338114|pmid=28716914|pmc=5547614|volume=114|issue=31|pages=8402\u20138407}}</ref>\n | <!--Treatment--> \n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/PYGM PYGM] <br/>{{OMIM7|608455|PYGM}} <hr/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/glycogen-storage-disease-type-v GSD 5] <br/> {{OMIM7|232600|GSD 5}} <br/> {{GARD1|6528|GSD 5}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|368|GSD 5}}\n |- valign=\"top\"\n | [[Glycogenolysis]]&nbsp;step: <br/> Debranching of PLD {{Center|\u2013}}   [[Glycogen debranching enzyme]] (GDE)\n | AGL: <br/> Liver, muscles <hr/>  '''[[Glycogen storage disease type III|GSD type III]]''' <br/>(GSD 3, Forbes disease, Cori disease, limit dextrinosis, glycogen debrancher deficiency, GDE deficiency, AGL deficiency) \n | Infant or child onset, often at puberty some symptoms improve. <br/> '''Liver''': Hepatomegaly, growth retardation, hyperlipidemia, hypoglycemia. Occasional seizures related to hypoglycemia. Adult cirrhosis in some. <br/> '''Muscle''': Myopathy, muscular hypotonia, muscle wasting (distal, some limb-girdle, some proximal instead), hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. Slowly progressive muscle weakness. <br/> '''GSD IIIa / IIIc''': Liver and muscle <br/> '''GSD IIIb / IIId''': Liver only\n | <!--Diagnose--> '''Exercise test''': Severely impaired lactate response (muscle involvement). Normal or enhanced ammonia.<ref name=\"ischaemic\"/>\n | <!--Treatment--> \n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/AGL AGL] <br/>{{OMIM7|610860|AGL}} <hr/> {{nowrap|NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/glycogen-storage-disease-type-iii GSD 3]}} <br/> {{OMIM7|232400|GSD 3}} <br/> {{GARD1|9442|GSD 3}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|366|GSD 3}}\n|}\n\n===== Related to glycogenolysis =====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n |- valign=\"top\" \n ! Affected enzymatic function <br/>\u2013<br/> Enzyme <br/> (Relation to glycogenolysis)\n ! Gene: <br/> Organ(s) <hr/> Disease <br/>(Synonyms) \n ! {{nowrap|Reported symptoms.}} <br/> Forms (if applicable) <br> {{nobold|{{small|Note: Not all patients have all symptoms; severity and presentation can vary.}}}}\n ! Diagnostic tests \n ! Treatment \n ! References <br/> and links \n |- valign=\"top\"\n | Glycogenolysis final step: <br/> Release of G-1-P {{Center|\u2013}} [[Phosphorylase kinase, alpha 1]] <br/> (Activation of liver glycogen phosphorylase, c.f. GSD 6) \n | [[PHKA2]]: <br/> Liver (GSD 9a) <br/> [[PHKB]]: <br/> Liver, Muscle (GSD 9b) <br/> [[PHKG2]]: <br/> Liver (GSD 9c) <hr/> \n'''[[Glycogen storage disease type IX|GSD type IX]]''' <br/>(GSD 9, phosphorylase b kinase deficiency, PhK deficiency, liver glycogenosis) <br/> {{nowrap|'''Formerly GSD type VIII'''}} (GSD&nbsp;8)\n | '''GSD 9a: Liver form.''' Hepatomegaly, growth retardation, elevation of glutamate-pyruvate transaminase and glutamate-oxaloacetate transaminase, hypercholesterolemia, hypertriglyceridemia, and fasting hyperketosis. Improves with age, most adult patients are asymptomatic. <br/> '''GSD 9a1''': PhK deficiency in erythrocytes. <br/> '''GSD 9a2''': Normal PhK activity in erythrocytes. <br/> '''GSD 9b: Liver and muscle form.''' Additionally mild myopathy like GSD 9d. Rare. <br/> '''GSD 9c''':  Similar to GSD 9a, but tends to be more severe. In some hepatic fibrosis or cirrhosis.\n | <!--Diagnose--> '''Exercise test''': Muscle involvement see GSD 9d.\n | <!--Treatment--> \n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/PHKA2 PHKA2] <br/>{{OMIM7|300798|PHKA2}} <br/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/PHKB PHKB] <br/>{{OMIM7|172490|PHKB}} <br/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/PHKG2 PHKG2] <br/>{{OMIM7|172471|PHKG2}} <hr/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/glycogen-storage-disease-type-ix GSD 9] <br/> {{ORPHA1|370|GSD 9}} <br/> {{OMIM7|306000|GSD&nbsp;9a1/9a2}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|264580|GSD&nbsp;9a/9c}} <br/> {{OMIM7|261750|GSD 9b}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|79240|GSD 9b}} <br/> {{OMIM7|613027|GSD 9c}} \n |- valign=\"top\"\n | Glycogenolysis final step: <br/> Release of G-1-P {{Center|\u2013}} [[Phosphorylase kinase, alpha 1]] <br/> (Activation of muscle glycogen phosphorylase, c.f. GSD 5) \n | [[PHKA1]]: <br/> Muscle <hr/>  '''[[Glycogen storage disease type IX|GSD type IX]]d''' <br/>(GSD 9d, phosphorylase b kinase deficiency, PhK deficiency, muscle glycogenosis) <br/> {{nowrap|'''Formerly GSD type VIII'''}} (GSD&nbsp;8) <br/> {{nowrap|'''Formerly GSD type Vb'''}} (GSD&nbsp;5b)<ref>GeneReviews: [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK55061/ Phosphorylase Kinase Deficiency]</ref>\n | Myopathy. Exercise-induced muscle weakness or stiffness. Relative mild compared to other metabolic myopathies. Typically adult-onset, some asymptomatic in late adulthood. No liver involvement.\n | <!--Diagnose--> '''Exercise test''': Both impaired and normal lactate observed; possible submaximal/maximal or aerobic/anaerobic discrepancy. Normal or exaggerated ammonia response.<ref>{{OMIM7|300559|GSD 9d}}</ref>\n | <!--Treatment--> \n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/PHKA1 PHKA1] <br/>{{OMIM7|311870|PHKA1}} <hr/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/glycogen-storage-disease-type-ix GSD 9] <br/> {{OMIM7|300559|GSD 9d}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|715|GSD 9d/9e}}\n |- valign=\"top\"\n | Degradation of glycogen to glucose in [[lysosome]]s {{Center|\u2013}} [[Acid alpha-glucosidase]] <br/> (Alternative pathway to glycogenolysis) \n | GAA: <br/> Myopathy <hr/> '''[[Glycogen storage disease type II|GSD type II]]''' <br/>(GSD 2, Pompe's disease, acid maltase deficiency, deficiency of lysosomal alpha-glucosidase, cardiomegalia glycogenica) \n | '''Classic infantile form (Pompe disease)''': Cardiomyopathy and muscular hypotonia. In some respiratory involvement. <br/> '''Juvenile and adult form''': Myopathy of the skeletal muscles. Some similarity to limb-girdle dystrophy. In some respiratory involvement. <br/> '''Non-classic infantile form''': Less severe.\n | <!--Diagnose-->\n | <!--Treatment--> \n | NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/gene/GAA GAA] <br/>{{OMIM7|606800|GAA}} <hr/> NLM/GHR:[https://ghr.nlm.nih.gov/condition/pompe-disease GSD 2] <br/> {{OMIM7|232300|GSD 2}} <br/> {{GARD1|5714|GSD 2}} <br/> {{ORPHA1|365|GSD 2}}\n|}\n\nMutations in the PRKAG2 gene have been traced to fatal congenital nonlysosomal cardiac glycogenosis; PRKAG2 is a noncatalytic gamma subunit of [[AMP-activated protein kinase]] (AMPK), which affects the release of G-1-P by phosphorylase kinase during nonlysosomal glycogenolysis.<ref>{{OMIM7|602743|PRKAG2}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|   DiseasesDB     = \n}}\n{{Medical resources\n|ICD10          = {{ICD10|E|73||e|70}}-{{ICD10|E|74||e|70}} |\n|ICD9           = {{ICD9|271}} |\n|ICDO           = |\n|OMIM           = |\n|MedlinePlus    = |\n|eMedicineSubj  = |\n|eMedicineTopic = |\n|MeshID         = D002239 |\n}}\n{{Carbohydrate metabolic pathology}}\n{{Mucopolysaccharidoses}}\n{{Glycoproteinoses}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Inborn errors of Carbohydrate Metabolism}}\n[[Category:Diabetes]]\n[[Category:Inborn errors of carbohydrate metabolism]]\n", "name_user": "62.238.220.59", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(table on UGP2 was updated, as it was recently found to be a disease gene for a new epilepsy syndrome)", "ur